Capítulo 1

 

 

1.INTRODUCCIÓN   

1.1.    Alcance y propósito

 

       jsUML2 [1] es una librería JavaScript/HTML5 que permite a cualquier desarrollador generar aplicaciones que requieran el manejo de diagramas UML2 en su web, de forma fácil y rápida, sin necesidad de programar toda la funcionalidad desde cero. Haciendo uso de un número reducido de funciones de interfaz, se pueden generar los diagramas más habituales de los tipos especificados en el estándar. De la misma forma, la librería ofrece soporte para definir perfiles UML como medio para extender el propio UML [2], y así poder extender los elementos UML ya incorporados en la librería. Esto permite la personalización de los diagramas presentados al usuario.

       Otro punto de gran importancia es el referente a la posibilidad de extensión de la librería a partir de métodos y objetos diseñados para este propósito. De esta forma, se da la posibilidad de extender las funcionalidades ofrecidas por la librería, así como la mejora y depuración de las ya existentes, con el fin de que la librería se pueda adaptar lo máximo posible a las necesidades de la aplicación externa que la use.

       Uno de los aspectos fundamentales en el diseño de jsUML2 ha sido el uso de UML 2 como lenguaje de modelado, según la definición establecida por OMG (Object Management Group) [3]. UML fue diseñado para ser un lenguaje de modelado de propósito general, lo que da una mayor flexibilidad a la hora de modelar sistemas. Al ser un lenguaje de propósito general, hay ocasiones en las que no se puede utilizar adecuadamente en dominios concretos de un problema, por lo que se tiene que extender el propio lenguaje para adaptarlo a los mismos. OMG ofrece varias soluciones, entre las que cabe destacar el uso de perfiles UML o UML profiles, los cuales especializan y restringen algunos de los conceptos del lenguaje UML.

            In a first version of this library, the initial architecture was developed, in addition to:

 

§   Most important objects in the core of the library (diagram, node and relation).

§   Final library objects that comply with the UML2 standard and that are included in the diagrams of use cases, classes, components and sequence (only basic elements).

§   A demonstration editor of the library that aims to show the use of the different functionalities of the library provided so far.

 

       In a second evolution, these objects are extended and new diagrams are incorporated (diagrams of state and activity machines), as well as the extension of existing diagrams, in the case of the sequence diagram, which had a basic structure. Along with each diagram, information is provided on the final objects available. Another point that this manual takes into account is the one corresponding to the definition of profiles and the different valid objects for a profile. Finally, a practical example of an application that makes use of the library and that shows the new features incorporated into it is presented: the jsUML2 editor. Please note that this editor is a demo tool and is not intended to be exhaustive in terms of usability, completeness, and design.

       This manual is intended for the programmer who wants to make use of the library's functionalities without needing to know how these functionalities are developed internally, and should not be considered a user manual for the included demo editor.

1.4.     Document description

 

This document is not intended to be an exhaustive development manual with the library, which on the other hand is open to modifications by the programmer. The objective is to mark the necessary guides for the complete understanding of the library code and to facilitate its subsequent integration in third-party projects.

The following chapters describe the different layers that make up development, as well as its basic elements. Subsequently, each type of diagram and its objects are introduced, including the UML profiles. Finally we discuss about the sample application and other development aspects related to the library.

 

 

 

 

Chapter 2

 

2.   INSTALLATION AND UNINSTALLATION

 

       To correctly understand the library installation process, you must know its structure, which is made up of two parts or layers:

 

§   UDCore : It is the core of the library, so it concentrates most of the functionality and complexity. Its functions range from drawing lines and shapes, to handling and interacting with diagram elements, all regardless of the inherent characteristics of UML.

§   UDModules : This is a higher layer than the previous one, it is in charge of designing the specific elements of UML2 on elements generated by the core layer. The final objects of the diagrams are implemented in it, giving them the shape and characteristics required by the standard.

 

       Any application that makes use of the library will constitute a third upper layer, which will be supported by UDModules .

       The components of the library are made up of a multitude of class files, style sheets and images. However, for use within a web application it is an essential requirement to minimize the number of files to improve the transfer of the library over the network. By default the entire library has been packed and compressed into just two JavaScript files , a common style sheet and an image directory. However, we recommend that the programmer regenerate the files including only the UML elements that are going to be used.

       Its installation is detailed below in section 2.1 . However, if the library requires any changes or is interested in expanding its functionality with new diagrams, it will require the use of special tools and a broader knowledge that will be explained in section 2.2 .

 

2.1.     Library installation

 

       The final files for the library, ready for use in an application, are located in the ./build directory , the structure of which is detailed below.

           

 / build: Directory containing the files for the use of the application

·          . / css   - Directory of style sheets required for library elements.

·          ./Img - Directory of images necessary for the use of the library.

·          UDCore.js - Packaged and compressed file with the core of the library.

·          UDModules.js - Packaged and compressed file with the final diagrams of UML2.

 

       For the library to work properly, you must include the / css , / img directories , as well as the UDCore.js and UDModules.js files .

       Next, it will be necessary to add the tags that link to the JavaScript source files and the style sheet, inside the <head> </head> tag , this being the header of the HTML document:

 

            <link type = 'text / css' rel = 'stylesheet' href = 'css / UDStyle.css' media = 'screen' />

<script type = 'text / javascript' src = 'UDCore.js'> </script>

<script type = 'text / javascript' src = 'UDModules.js'> </script>

 

       Although the code presented in the previous lines chooses the current document of the application as the path for the UDCore and UDModules files , this does not mean that these files must be included here. However, the dependency order of the boxes indicated above is important and, therefore, that the link to the UDCore.js file occurs before any other related to the library, since it is in charge of providing the basic functions and elements. to the next layer. UDModules.js then provides the final objects for the UML2 diagrams.

      

2.2.     Bookstore packaging

 

       In most cases it is not necessary to perform this task, only if:

§   You want to add or remove a diagram from the library.

§   You have changed the functionality of the library and need to repackage it.

 

       In any case, the following applications explained in the following sections will be necessary. For your convenience it is recommended to run them in Linux environment.

 

2.2.1.   Sprocketize

 

       Sprocketize [5] is the application that allows to resolve dependencies between the different Javascript modules , since the language does not have a native way of performing this task. After having correctly installed the application, it is in charge of analyzing all the JavaScript source files and packaging them into one.

       Note that it is necessary to have previously installed a current version of the Ruby programming language for Sprocketize to work properly . Since this is beyond the scope of this manual, the reader is encouraged to refer to the Quick Installation Guide [6].

       Once you have the Ruby environment completely installed, you must proceed to the installation of Sprocketize, which is as simple as executing the following command line under any Linux environment.

 

gem install --remote sprockets

 

       If you find any errors, you can go to the application's web page [5].

 

2.2.2.    YUICompressor

 

       YUICompressor [7] is a small application whose function is to compress JavaScript code , producing source files as well but with a very appreciable reduction in size, around 40% depending on the content.

       Such application is a component of the programming library in Javascript of Yahoo ,

YUI ( Yahoo User Interface ) included in the distribution of the yuicompressor.jar library , for the convenience of the developers. Since your development language is Java, you must have the Java virtual machine installed to use it .

 

2.2.3.    Packaging and compression

 

       Once the necessary applications are installed, it is important to know the distribution of the files within the source directory of jsUML2.

All the necessary files for the library, as well as style sheets and images, are located inside the / src directory as detailed below:

 

/ src / - Directory of library sources.

·          Core / - Directory with the files corresponding to the core of the library, that is, the UDCore component .

·          Modules / - Directory formed by the directories that contain the files corresponding to each of the UML2 diagrams.

o     class / - Directory with the final objects available for the class diagram.

or     usecase / - Directory with the final objects available for the use case diagram.

o     component / - Directory with the final objects available for the component diagram.

o     generic / - Directory that contains the final objects of generic use for any diagram and the properties referring to the stereotyping of the final elements of the library.

o     sequence / - Directory with the final objects available for the sequence diagram.

o     activity / - Directory with the final objects available for the activity diagram.

o     stateMachine / - Directory with the final objects available for the state machine diagram.

o     profile / - Directory with the final objects available for the definition of a UML profile.

 

       So when the library is packaged it extracts the information about the diagrams from the / modules directory , therefore if you want certain specific diagrams within your application, you only have to add or remove the ones you want inside that directory and package everything again.

       The packaging and compression process of the library is simple: a file called make.sh is provided in the library distribution, assuming a Linux environment . Executing this script completes the entire process and the files in the / build directory are overwritten by the new ones, freeing the developer from understanding the commands used in the Sprocketize and YUICompressor applications .

 

       Once the process is done, the packaged files of the library are overwritten, the installation of the new files is carried out in the same way as it is done with the files distributed by default and do not require any additional procedure.

 

2.3.     Uninstall

 

       The uninstallation process of the library is simple, just delete the files that were copied when installing the library.

       In addition, it must be remembered that during the installation some lines of HTML code were added, necessary for the inclusion of the Javascript files of the library and the corresponding style sheet. Those lines must be erased too. If there is any doubt, they present the following aspect (or similar):

 

<link type = 'text / css' rel = 'stylesheet' href = 'css / UDStyle.css' media = 'screen' />

<script type = 'text / javascript' src = 'UDCore.js'> </script>

<script type = 'text / javascript' src = 'UDModules.js'> </script>

 

 

 

 

 

 

Chapter 3

 

3.      DESCRIPTION OF THE OBJECTS

 

       As we said at the beginning of chapter 2, the library is made up of a two-layer architecture: the UDCore layer , which corresponds to the graphic core of the library, and the UDModules layer , which contains both the diagrams supported by the library and the final objects of UML2. In this chapter, an in-depth description of each of the layers will be carried out, revealing the base objects on which the functionality of the library is based so that a developer can make use of them.

 

3.1.     Graphic Core Layer: UDCore

 

       In this section we will detail the interface of the most important objects within the core of the library. First, we must be aware that jsUML2 structures its specifications in independent diagrams (with the exception of profiles), which basically consist of graphic elements joined together as a graph in terms of sides and edges (Relation). These nodes and relationships have common behaviors, regardless of the particular visual appearance and functionality they exhibit when they specialize in a particular UML2 element.

 

§   Diagram : Understand the drawing canvas and its internal logic. Its function is to organize the elements of the diagram and manipulate them at the request of the programmer, as well as to offer an adequate handling of the events generated by the user and transmit these to the different elements that make up the diagram. From this class they inherit all the specific diagrams of UML2, and with it all its functionality.

§   Node : They are each of the simple shaped elements that make up a diagram, for example a class or a package. Among its functions is to offer the possibility of movement, resizing and modification of its properties. All non-composite elements present in the diagram that are not relationships inherit from this class.

§   SuperNode : They are each of the shaped elements that are present in the diagram, made up of two or more Node objects (called regions). For example, they can be a ' Combined Fragment ' ( Alternative, Loop, Break, Option ), a region or an Activity Partition . Among its functions are all those offered by the Node object , as well as new functions related to the creation of new nodes within its structure, and to the resizing and modification of their properties.

§   Relation : They are the relationships between the different elements of the diagram, whether they are nodes or relationships. They allow modifying their attributes as well as moving their position through the diagram generating intermediate points. All relationships in the diagram inherit from this class.

§   NodeFigure: It is the object in charge of defining the graphic representation of a node. All figures that are used for the graphic representation of a final object inherit from this class.

 

       Other objects will be explained in detail below. Later, in section 3.4 (Objects for the development of new elements) specific additional functions will be detailed in the event that the programmer wishes to create his own type of diagrams, and not only those already available.

 

3.1.1.   Diagram Object

 

       It is the main object of the library in charge of managing the elements of the diagram. The functions available for diagram management are:

 

·          Constructor ({id: String, width: Number, height: Number}) Thus we will call the function that is invoked when the element is created using the new keyword , that is, to instantiate a new object of the class. JSON notation is used to pass parameters to constructor functions, since it provides important advantages in class inheritance. Therefore, the parameters indicated here must be entered in braces and with their appropriate identifier, the order is not important.

o     id (String) The name of the id of a div element of the HTML document. This element will be in charge of containing the HTML structure of the diagram to be generated.

o     width (Number) Width of the diagram to be created.

o     height (Number) Height of the diagram to be created.

·          Constructor () A second option is to invoke the constructor without parameters. This will create a diagram element, but will require further initialization using the initialize function . It is useful when the management of Canvas elements is done by the application and not by the diagram. Therefore, it will be necessary to pass this information to the diagram before using it.

·          AddElement (Element) Adds an element of type Element to the diagram in its relative position with respect to those that already exist inside. For example, if you add a UML class where there is already a UML package using this function, this class automatically becomes part of the package.

·          AddRelationFromPoints (Relation, Number, Number, Number, Number): Boolean   Adds a relationship, passed as a parameter, between two elements. These elements are identified by their x and y coordinates respectively. The method returns true if the relationship could be successfully added to the diagram, otherwise it returns false.

·          CheckForParent (Element) Checks by the position of the element if its current parent has stopped containing it. If so, the parent reference to the element that now contains it is changed.

·          DelElement (Element) Removes an element from the diagram, which implies removing all the elements contained or dependent on it. For example, if we delete a UML package, the elements that are inside it will be eliminated and, also, their relations.

·          Draw () Updates the Canvas object with the current state of the diagram.

·          GetElementByPoint (x: number, y: number) : Element Returns the object of type Element that is in the indicated position within the diagram.

·          GetId (): Number Provides the identification number of the diagram, previously assigned to it. This method is useful when controlling multiple diagrams in the same application.

·          GetName (): String Returns the name assigned to the diagram. This name is the one that shows the diagram in its graphic representation, usually in the upper left, inside a tab. It can be modified using the setName function .

·          GetXML (): XMLObject Returns an object of type XML managed by Javascript, which contains the tree of the diagram structure in XML format.

·          GetXMLString (): String Returns the structure of the serialized diagram in XML format within a character string.

·          Initialize (id, div, mainContext, motionContext, width, height) This function is in charge of assigning the elements that the diagram will use for its representation, as well as some size values.

o     id (Number): Indicates the identification number of the diagram, like the setId method .

o     div (HTMLElement) Is the reference to the document node, of type div , where the diagram is located.

o     mainContext (CanvasRenderingContext2D) It is the context element that Canvas uses as an interface to draw on it. Obtained using the getContext ('2d') function of the Canvas element .

o     motionContext (CanvasRenderingContext2D) It is the context of the Canvas object that draws the animations of the diagram, such as the movements of the objects when dragging the mouse. It must be above the main Canvas for them to be seen correctly.

o     width (Number) The width of the Canvas object being used.

o     height (Number) The height of the Canvas object being used.

·          Interaction (Boolean) This method enables or disables editing / interaction with the user. In other words, it paralyzes the flow of events from the user and does not allow the user to interact with the diagram. This function is activated or deactivated by means of a Boolean type variable.

·          IsVisible (): Boolean Returns if the element is visible.

·          NotifyChange () This method, usually called by another object, notifies the diagram that an object has been modified and, therefore, the canvas has to be refreshed.

·          NotifyDeleted (Element) Notifies the diagram that an element has been deleted and therefore if it belongs to the diagram it has to be deleted from it too.

·          NotifyDraw () This method, usually called by another object, notifies the diagram that the canvas has to be refreshed. This method performs the same functionality as notifyChange () in the case of the Diagram object . However, this is not the case for Node objects .

·          ReassignRelationTo (Relation, Number, Number) Returns the element that matches the coordinates passed as a parameter, as long as it is different from the relation received as an argument. This method is usually invoked by an element of type Relation , in order to know which element coincides with one end of it.

·          SetBackgroundNodes (String) This method is in charge of setting the background color of the diagram elements. changing the default color that the elements of the canvas will show.

·          SetId (Number) Assigns the identification number indicated to the diagram, in order to identify it within a larger application.

·          SetName (String) Assigns the indicated name to the diagram. This modification is visually displayed in the upper left corner of the drawing canvas.

·          SetUpdateHeightCanvas (boolean) This method enables or disables the resizing of the canvas height in case an object defined on a diagram exceeds the maximum height set on the canvas . In other words, this method aims to free the external application from any extra programming to resize the canvas . To do this, simply enter a Boolean value true / false as a method parameter . 

·          SetXML (XMLObject) Generates the elements of the diagram contained in the XML structure that is passed to it as a parameter. This function is useful when the diagram is inside another larger application with its own XML structure, if several diagrams have to be initialized at the same time.

·          SetXMLString (String) Generates the elements of a diagram contained in the character string with a valid XML format for the library.

·          StopEvents () Stops the flow of user events if it is active. For example, if there is a selected item or a window open, they are closed. However, it does not prevent the user from continuing to interact with it, as does the interaction method .

·          UpdateHeightCanvas () Resize the canvas so that no element is outside of it.

 

An important detail when creating an application with the library is to understand how the library handles Canvas elements , and it is best to express it with the scheme shown in Figure 3.1. As can be seen in the image, two Canvas- type objects overlap . In the lower layer (main canvas) the state of the diagram is reflected and in the upper layer (motion canvas) the result of the interaction with the user, such as the displacement of the figures. This is necessary so as not to overload the rendering engine with constant and complex updates, which is most noticeable in larger diagrams.

 

 

 

Figure 3.1: Structure of layered canvas elements

 

3.1.2.   Node object

 

       It is any node not composed in the graph of the diagram. In general, there can be different types of nodes depending on their shape, but they all share the interface that defines them.

 

·          Constructor ({x: Number, y: Number}) Is the constructor of the class. Supports passing coordinates using JSON notation.

o     x (Number) : Position on the x axis of the node to be created.

o     y (Number): Position on the y axis of the node to be created.

·          Constructor () This class allows the use of a constructor without parameters, which places the node at the default coordinate origin.

·          AddChild (Element) Adds an element to the node's child list. In this way, when a change is made on the node, it propagates correctly to its children.

·          AddItem (Array, HTMLDiv) Adds an object to the menu that contains the DIV. This object is specified by means of an Array whose first position indicates what action should be performed when it is pressed and its second position indicates what the text will be shown in said menu option.

 

f.addItem ([f.showDirectionDialog (), 'Direction'], 'divBlock1');

 

·          AddRelation (Relation) Adds an element of type Relation to the node, this means that the node becomes part of the relationship and will also keep a reference to it in order to correctly propagate future changes that may be made to it.

·          AddValue (String, String) Its function is similar to that of setValue , but applied to components whose content is multiple and does not retract to a single value. For example, the stereotype labels of an object or the attributes of a class can be several. Every time we call this function, a new component is created inside the node, which will contain the value indicated in the second parameter. For example, if we want to add an attribute to a UML 2 class, just execute the following code:

 

var c = new UMLClass ();

c.addValue ('attributes', '+ new_attribute_of_class: int');

 

·          DelChild (Element) Deletes a child list element from the node. Thus, when a change is made on the node, it will not propagate to the element in question.

·          DelComponent (Component) Deletes the component in question as long as it belongs to the node.

·          DelRelation (Relation) Removes a node from a relationship.

·          Deselect () Deselects the current node and closes all open dialogs associated with it.

·          Draw (Canvas) Draws the node, its figures and components on the canvas .

·          DrawShape (Canvas) Draws the border of the node on the canvas .

·          GetArea (): Number  Returns the area occupied by the node, calculated from the height and width of the rectangle that frames it.

·          GetCentralPoint (): Point Returns the center point of the node.

·          GetComponents (): Array Returns a list with the components of the invoking node.

·          GetElementXML (Element): XMLNode Returns the serialized node in XML format. It is necessary to pass the parent of the element as a parameter.

·          GetFontColor (): String This method returns the font color that is assigned by default to each new component that is added to the node. The format is defined by the CSS 2.1 standard to define the color.

·          GetFontFamily (): String This method returns the font family, which is assigned by default to each component added to the node. The format is defined by the CSS 2.1 standard to define font families.

·          GetId (): Number Provides the identification number of the node, previously assigned to it. This method is useful when controlling multiple nodes in the same application and each one must be identified in order to differentiate them. It can be modified using the setId () function .

·          GetLineWidth (): Number  This method returns the line width with which the node is drawn.

·          GetLineColor (): String Returns the color of the line with which the node is drawn.

·          GetLinkCentered (Number, Number): Point  Returns the point belonging to the edge of the node from which a straight line could be drawn up to the coordinates passed as a parameter, without going inside the node and in such a way that the length of the line be as few as possible. This function is used to find out from where the edge of the node can draw a line (eg association) that begins or ends at its edge, to the coordinates of another node.

·          GetMovement (): Point Returns a point that indicates the movement of the node with respect to its last position. The point stores the distance between the x and y coordinates of your current position and its just previous position.

·          GetMenu (): Array Returns the Array of information regarding the context menu of the node. It can be set using the setMenu () function .

·          GetNodeChilds (): Array Returns a list with the child nodes of the invoking node.

·          GetParent (): Node Returns the parent node of the current one.

·          GetParticularHeigth (Number): Array   Returns the value of the y coordinate and the width of the node if the y coordinate , passed as a parameter, belongs to the range in which the node exists for the abscissa axis, that is, if the value of the parameter It is between the initial x coordinate of the node and its width plus the initial value. The return value is an Array whose first position matches the y coordinate of the node and the second position matches its height.

·          GetParticularWidth (Number): Array Returns the value of x and the width of the node if the y coordinate passed as a parameter belongs to the node's range for the abscissa axis, that is, if the parameter value is between the initial y coordinate of the node and its height plus the initial value. The return value is an Array whose first position matches the x coordinate of the node and the second position matches its width.

·          GetX (): Number Returns the x coordinate relative to the node position.

·          GetY (): Number Returns the y coordinate relative to the node position.

·          Height (Number): Boolean  It has the same behavior as the setHeight (Number) function , but it also checks the type of the parameter as Number , returning false otherwise or if an error occurs. If everything is correct, update the node once its new height has been established.

·          IsChildOf (Node): Boolean Indicates if the node is a child of the node passed as a parameter.

·          IsContainer (): Boolean Indicates if the node is a container, that is, if the node can include any type of element created in the diagram inside it. This property can be set during the definition of the Node element using the setContainer () function .

·          IsOver (Number, Number) Checks if the given point is positioned on the node. In the affirmative case it returns true, in another false case.

·          IsOverBeforePosition (Number, Number) Checks if the given point is positioned on the previous node position. If yes it returns true. In another false case. The previous position refers to the center point of the node before the node last moved. If the current and previous positions were not moved or matched using the resetMovement () method , the previous position will match the current position.

·          NotifyChange () Tells the node ( Node object ) that some of the related elements have been modified and, therefore, must be updated to reflect their new state.

·          NotifyDeleted (Relation)  Notifies the node that a relation ( Relation object ) has been removed and therefore its reference has to be removed as well.

·          NotifyDraw () The node indicates to its diagram that it must update the canvas , because some of the elements that make up the node have been modified.

·          Position (Number, Number) Modifies the coordinates of the node to the indicated position. The first argument is the coordinate on the x axis and the second argument is the coordinate on the y axis. This position corresponds to the upper left corner of the node, with respect to the upper left corner of the diagram.

·          Remove () Deletes the node, as well as the reference that its father kept on it and all the elements that depend on its existence. Specifically, these elements are: the children of the node (if this is a container node) and the relationships in which it participates. It also notifies the change to its parent element by calling the notifyChange () method using the internal reference it stores on it.

·          RemoveContextualMenu () Deletes the context menu of the HTML document.

·          ResetMovement () Set the previous node position as the current one. The movement of the node becomes 0.

·          Select (Number, Number) Checks whether the node matches the coordinates indicated as a parameter. If yes, the node is selected. If these coordinates also coincide with any of its components, it is also selected.

·          SetBackgroundColor (String) This method is in charge of defining the color with which the node figures will be drawn. Its parameter is a string that corresponds to the RGB color that you want to associate with the node.

·          SetDiagram (Diagram) Modifies the property that determines the diagram to which the node belongs.

·          SetElementXML (XMLNode) Sets the properties of the node using the information contained in the XML node. The information of a serialized node can be obtained in XML format using the getElementXML () function .

·          SetFontColor (color: String) Modifies the font color that is assigned by default to each new component added to the node, and the font color of all its current components, as a parameter passed to the function:

o     color: string Defines the font color defined by the CSS 2.1 standard.

·          SetFontFamily (font-family: String) Modify the font family that is assigned by default to each new component added to the node, and the font family of all its current node components:

o     font-family: string Defines the font family to be given to each component that is added to the default node. This format must respect the one defined by the CSS 2.1 standard to define font families.

·          SetHeigth (Number) Modifies the height of the element to that indicated by the numerical value passed as a parameter to the function. If the parameter is less than the minimum height defined for the node, the latter will be set as the height of the node. Remember that this minimum value can be modified using the setMinHeigth () function .

·          SetId (Number) Assigns the identification number indicated to the node, in order to identify it within the application.

·          SetLineColor (color: String) Modifies the color of the line with which the node is drawn:

o     color: string Defines the line color. The format must respect that defined by the CSS 2.1 standard.

·          SetLineWidth (Number) Modifies the width, passed as a parameter, of the line with which the node is drawn.

·          SetMenu (array) This method is in charge of defining the different items or elements that the context menu of a node will contain when you click on it with the right mouse button. The parameter consists of a two-dimensional array where each of the options in the context menu is defined, along with the actions to be performed when clicking on each option. Below is an example to clarify a little more the format that this array should have :

 

                     f.setMenu ([[actions0, option_name0],

                                          [actions1, option_name1],

                                          [actions2, option_name2]]);

 

                     f.setMenu (

                                    [[f.showColorDialog (), "Node Color"],

                                   [setVisibility (! isVisible ()), Hide / Show]]);

 

     being f a UML object defined in the file objects.js of a diagram, the context menu created in the first generic example for this purpose consist of 3 options with corresponding actions to the press about each of them.

·          SetParent (Node) Sets the node passed as parameter as the parent node.

·          SetSelectedFigure (Number) Indicates which figure of the node is going to be drawn from the list of figures of the node. If the figure is an image, the components of the node will not be shown. Figures can be added or deleted with the addFigure () and delFigure () methods . Subsequently, in section 3.4.5, the different types of figures that are defined will be explained.

·          SetValue (String, String) This function is used to modify the values ​​of the subparts that make up the node. Each component of the node receives an identifier in the form of a text string, and through this identifier we can modify its values. For example, the UMLClass object determines its name using a component whose identifier is name . Executing the following code we can change the name of a class.

 

var c = new UMLClass ();

c.setValue ('name', 'New class name');

 

·          SetVisibility (boolean) This method is in charge of establishing the visibility of a node. In other words, a true value of the method will make the node visible, as well as any element contained within it. Conversely, a false value will cause the node (and any element contained within it) not to be represented graphically in the diagram, and will not allow any type of interaction with the node by the user. It is recommended to limit the use of this method.

·          SetWidth (Number) Modifies the width of the element to that indicated by the numerical value passed as a function parameter. If the parameter is less than the minimum width defined for the node, this last value will be set as the width of the node. Remember that this minimum can be modified using the setMinWidth () function .

·          ShowColorDialog () This method is in charge of showing a dialog box to the user, through which the user can modify the background color with which the node is drawn. 

·          ShowContextualMenu (Number, Number) Shows the context menu of the node. This can be set using the setMenu () function . The x and y coordinates indicate the upper right point of the menu.

·          ShowStyleDialog () This method is in charge of displaying a dialog box, through which the user can modify the background color, the font color, the line color, the line width, the font size, the font family and style of the font, node, and all its components.

·          ToString (): String Returns a string with the name of the object, in this case, with the value 'Node'.

·          UpdateContainer () If the node is a container, it is resized to house the elements it contains. The node can be set as a container using the setContainer () function .

·          UpdatePosition (Number, Number, Boolean) The node position is updated as indicated by the offset on the x- axis and on the y- axis passed by parameters. The parameter of type Boolean indicates if the method has been called due to a displacement produced in a region.

·          Width (Number): Boolean  It has the same behavior as the setWidth (Number) function , but it also checks the type of the parameter as Number , returning false otherwise or if an error occurs. If everything is correct, update the node once its new width has been established.

 

In section 3.4.2 the specific functions required for creating a new node is displayed.

 

3.1.3.   SuperNode object

 

       It is any object composed in turn of two or more nodes called regions, to which the possibility of movement by the canvas is restricted independently and is limited to the movement made by the supernode as a complete unit. Being an object that inherits from the library Node object , it can make use of all the functions offered by the Node object , as well as new functions related to the creation of subnodes within its structure, and to the resizing and modification of their properties.

       We will detail the use of each of the methods provided by the SuperNode class (excluding properties derived from Node ).

 

§   Constructor ({x: number, y: number, orientation: number, includeComponentByRegion: boolean})  The constructor of the superNode class supports the passing of coordinates using JSON notation .

·          X Position on the x axis relative to the diagram where it will be included.

·          And position on the y axis on the diagram where it is to be included.

·          Orientation Structure Orientation SuperNode , may be vertical (numerical value 1) or horizontally (numerical value: 0).

·          IncludeComponentByRegion : if you want to include a component for the name tag in each of the regions contained in the SuperNode structure ( true value ) or you don't want it ( false value ).

§   Constructor () This class allows the use of a constructor without parameters, which by default places the element at the coordinate origin. Also, the default orientation of the SuperNode would be horizontal, and a component would be included for the name of each one of the regions contained in the structure.

§   addRegion (Node) Adds a region or node to the supernode structure, the first and only argument being the region that you want to add as a child.

§   deleteRegion (Node) Deletes a region or node belonging to the supernode.

 

 

3.1.4.   Relation object

 

This class is the base of all the relations (edges between nodes) existing in the diagrams of the library. Its interface functions are as follows:

·          Constructor ({a: Element, b: Element}) It is the constructor of the class, it supports the passing of the elements involved in the relation using JSON notation.

or     a (Element) It is the initial element of the relationship, if there is a difference between the two.

or     b (Element) It is the final element of the relation. 

·          Constructor () The class also has a constructor without parameters. Its use requires that the definition of related objects be done later using the setElements function .

·          AddRelation (Relation) The invoking relation of the function will keep a reference to the Relation type object passed as a parameter, so that it guarantees that future changes will be propagated correctly. This method is usually called when the object that invokes it becomes an end of this relationship.

·          AddValue (String, String) Its function is similar to that of setValue , but this applies to components whose content is multiple and not just a single value. For example, the stereotypes of a relationship. Every time we call this function, a new component is created inside the element, which will contain the value indicated in the second parameter. For example, if we want to add a stereotype to a UML 2 aggregation relationship, just execute the following code.

 

var c = new UMLAggregation ();

c.addValue ('stereotype', 'new_stereotype');

 

·          DelRelation (Relation) The reference that could be saved by the invoking object to the relation passed as parameter will be deleted. This method is usually invoked when the object in question is no longer an end of the relation, or when the reference is no longer necessary.

·          Deselect () Clears the current relationship and closes all open dialogues related to it.

·          Draw (Canvas) Reflects the current state of the relation on the canvas.

·          DrawShape (Canvas) Reflects the border of the relation on the canvas.

·          GetCentralPoint (): Point Returns the center point of the relation.

·          GetDirection (): String   Returns the address of the relation in the form of a string: 'a' if it is directed towards end A; 'b' if directed towards end B; 'ab' if it is addressed to both ends of the relationship; 'none' if the relationship is not directed.

·          GetElementA (): Element  Returns the element associated with the end A of the relation.

·          GetElementB (): Element  Returns the element associated with end B of the relation.

·          GetElementXML (Element): XMLNode Returns the serialized relation in XML format. It is necessary to pass the parent of the element as a parameter.

·          GetId (): Number Provides the identification number of the relationship, previously assigned to it. This method is useful when controlling multiple relationships in the same application and each one must be identified in order to differentiate them. It can be modified using the setId () function .

·          GetLineColor (): String Returns the line color of the relation.

·          GetLineStyle (): String Returns the line style of the relation. It can be set using the setLineStyle () function .

·          GetLineWidth (): Number  This method returns the line width with which the relation is drawn on the canvas .

·          GetLinkCentered (Number, Number): Point Returns the intersection point between the coordinates passed as parameters and the relation.

·          GetParent (): Node Returns the parent node of the relation.

·          IsLinked (Element): Boolean Checks if the element in question belongs to the relation. If yes, it returns true and, otherwise, false.

·          IsOver (Number, Number) Checks if the point passed as a parameter is positioned on the relation.

·          NotifyChange () Indicates to the relation that some of the elements related to it, or some of its components, has been modified and, therefore, has to be updated.

·          NotifyDraw () The relation indicates to the diagram to which it belongs that it must be redrawn, since some of the elements that make up the relation have been modified.

·          Remove () Deletes the relation and all the dependent elements of it.

·          Select (Number, Number) Checks if the relation matches the indicated coordinates. If yes, it is selected. If these coordinates also coincide with any of its components, it is also selected.

·          SetDiagram (Diagram) Modifies the property that determines the diagram to which the relation belongs.

·          SetDirection (String) Sets the direction of the relation by drawing open arrows in the direction determined by the string passed as a parameter, that is: 'a' sets an arrow at the beginning of the relation (end A); 'b' sets an arrow at the end of the relationship (end B); 'ab' sets arrows at both ends of the relationship; 'none' sets no end to be drawn.

·          SetDirectionToA (Boolean) Sets the direction to the end A of the relation as indicated by the parameter passed to the function. If the value is true , then the address is set and drawn.

·          SetDirectionToB (Boolean) Sets the direction to the end B of the relation as indicated by the parameter passed to the function. If the value is true , then the address is set and drawn.

·          SetElementA (Element) Defines the initial element of the relation.

·          SetElementB (Element) Defines the final element of the relation.

·          SetElements (Element, Element) This function defines the elements belonging to the relation. The first element will be the initial and the second the final, if there is any difference between the two.

·          SetElementXML (XMLNode) Sets the properties of the relation using the information contained in the XML node. The information for a serialized relationship can be obtained in XML format using the getElementXML () function .

·          SetId (Number) Assigns the indicated identification number to the relation.

·          SetLineColor (color: string) Modifies the color of the relation line, as indicated as a parameter:

o     color: string Defines the color of the element, which must comply with the CSS 2.1 standard.

·          SetLineStyle (String) Sets the line style of the relation. Possible styles are "D ashed" and "S olid" . Subsequently, in section 3.4.6, the different types of lines are detailed.

·          SetLineWidth (Number) Modifies the width of the line with which the relation is drawn.

·          SetParent (Node) Set the Node object passed as parameter as the parent node of the relation.

·          SetValue (String, String) This function is used to modify the values ​​of the subparts that make up the relation, each component of the relation receives an identifier in the form of a character string, and by means of this identifier we can modify its values. For example, the UMLAgreggation relationship determines its name using a component whose identifier is name . By executing the following code we can change the name of an aggregation relation.

 

var c = new UMLAggregation ();

c.setValue ('name', 'new name');

 

·          ShowDirectionDialog () This method is in charge of displaying a dialog box through which the user can modify the address of the relation.

·          ShowStyleDialog () This method is in charge of displaying a dialog box through which the user can modify the color, line type and line width of the relation.

·          ToString (): String Returns a string that identifies the type of element, in this case with a value of 'Relation'.

§   updateParent () Updates the parent node of the relation. A parent node is understood as an object of type Node that is the container of both ends of the relationship, if it exists.

§   updatePosition (Number, Number) Updates the position of the relation and all its points, moving it as much as the parameters in the x and y axis indicate , respectively.

 

Consider that the showContextualMenu () , removeContextualMenu () , setMenu () , getMenu (), and addItem () functions exhibit behavior analogous to that exposed for the methods of the Node object .

 

3.1.5.   NodeFigure object

 

This is the object in charge of defining the graphic representation of a node. There are different types of shapes available:

 

§   AcceptEventActionFigure: This figure is used in the graphical representation of a UMLAcceptEventAction element (section 9.2 ).

§   CrossEllipseFigure: Figure showing a circle with a cross inside as a graphic representation. For example, it appears in the UMLFlowFinal (section 9.22 ) and UMLExitPoint   (section 8.6 ) elements .

§   CrossFigure: Type of figure representing a circular element with a cross in the shape of a cross. As an example we find UMLTerminate (section 8.4 ) .

§   EllipseFigure : Figure that draws an ellipse. This figure is used in the representation of the use cases, UMLCaseUse and UMLCaseUseExtended elements (see section 4.3).

§   ExpansionNodeFigure This figure consists of a rectangle divided into smaller rectangles by several lines. It creates an expansion node in an activity diagram, allows its graphical representation and is used in the graphical representation of the final element UMLExpansionNode (section 9.15 ).

§   FromImageFigure : Figure that draws an image external to the library. Its use is typical of UML profiles, thanks to which the different UML elements can take different custom forms.

§   HalfFilledEllipseFigure: This type of figure is represented by the outline of a circle that contains a smaller circle inside. It is used for the graphical representation of the final elements UMLActivityFinal (section 9.23 ) and UMLFinalState (section 8.3 ) present in the UDModules layer of the library.

§   LifelineFigure: Its representation consists of the drawing of a rectangle and, just below it, a vertical dashed line. This type of figure is used exclusively for the graphic representation of the UMLLifeline element (section 7.2) of the library.

§   NoteFigure : Figure that represents the characteristic icon of the notes, as represented by the UMLNote element exposed in section 11.1.

§   PackageFigure : Figure representing the typical folder icon for UML packages, represented in the UMLPackage element (see section 5.2).

§   RectangleFigure : Figure in the shape of a rectangle.

§   RegionFigure: Type of figure that draws a small rectangle and, below it, a larger rectangle with rounded edges. This graphical representation is used by the UMLVerticalRegion elements (section 8.10 ), UMLHorizontalRegion (section 8.11 ) and UMLCompositeState (section 8.9 ).

§   RhombusFigure: Figure that represents a diamond-shaped element. This figure is used by the UMLDecision_MergeNode element (section 9.19 ).

§   RoundedRectangleFigure: Type of figure that draws an element as a rectangle with rounded edges. This type of representation can be found in the elements UMLAction (section 9.5 ), UMLActivity (section 9.7 ) and UMLSimpleState (section 8.8 ).

§   SendSignalActionFigure: Figure used for the representation of the library element named UMLSendSignalAction (section 9.4 ).

§   StickmanFigure : Figure that draws the outline of the schematic man used in the use case diagrams, corresponding to the UMLActor element (section 4.2).

§   SwimlaneFigure: Figure that draws the outline of a rectangle, except the right side of it. This figure is used in the representation of the UMLHorizontalSwimlane elements (section 9.10 ) and UMLHorizontalHierarchicalSwimlane (section 9.12 ).

§   TimeEventFigure : Figure that allows the graphical representation of a final UMLTimeEvent element (section 9.3 ).

§   VerticalSwimlaneFigure: Figure that draws the outline of a rectangle, except the bottom side of it. This figure is used in the representation of the UMLVerticalSwimlane elements (section 9.11 ) and UMLVerticalHierarchicalSwimlane (section 9.13 ).

 

       The Figure 3.2 shows the generalization of these figures in class NodeFigure .

 


Figure 3 . 2 : Types of shapes for a node

 

On the other hand, the constructor of the NodeFigure class , from which the previously explained figure types inherit, receives the following parameters:

 

§   color: string - Defines the background color with which an element will be drawn. The format must respect that defined by the CSS 2.1 standard [10] to define color.

§   changeColorFigure: boolean - Allows (or does not allow) the modification of the figure's color once it has been established in the constructor. This parameter is defined to prevent UML elements that must always appear the same color, such as a start state or end state in the state machine diagram, from modifying their color and, therefore, their correct graphic representation. A true value of this parameter allows the color change, while a false value does not allow such change.

 

3.2.   UML diagramming layer: UDModules

 

       This section will detail the elements that make up the final objects designed to comply with the UML2 standard.

       The elements described here receive the properties of their parent classes and inherit their functionality, therefore, their handling is identical to the Diagram , Node , Relation or SuperNode type objects explained in section 3.1 . It is important to look at the identifiers that have been assigned to the components of each object to be able to manipulate their properties once they have been instantiated.

       The objects in the library have been named following a simple rule: they all start with the prefix 'UML' followed by the name of the element in English, capitalizing each word initial ( CamelCase notation ).

       Next, for each element its main characteristics will be described, as well as its graphic representation. The characteristics of each element will be presented in a table, as shown in Table 3.1 . In the case that an element represents a type of UML diagram, this table will not be used, it will simply indicate the name that the diagram receives within the library.

 

Object name : Name that the final object receives inside the library.

Inherits from

Parent class from which it inherits its properties. Among the possible parent classes we find Node , Relation and SuperNode .

Properties

List the different properties that distinguish the object.

Components

It lists the different components that the object incorporates and can be manipulated through the interface functions. You can distinguish between single or multiple components, depending on whether they contain one or more elements and, therefore, it would be modified with setValue or addValue .

Restrictions

Reports any type of restriction that may limit the use of the object under certain situations.

Table 3 . 1 : Template to define characteristics of an object

 

 

       To access the different components that a final object may contain, use is made of interface functions created specifically for that purpose. In this way, the programmer experience is improved and the internal structure of each object in the library is wrapped. Thus, the following enumeration shows the different identifiers common to all kinds of object components (note that the use of these properties will depend on the components present in each object, according to their definition), along with the interface functions for their access and modification. :

§   name [simple]: Name of the object. The following functions can be used to access this component:

·          SetName (String): Sets the name of the object.

·          GetName (): Returns a string with the name of the object.

§   stereotypes [multiple]: Stereotypes of the object. To obtain and modify the information of this component, the following functions are available:

·          AddStereotype (String): Adds a stereotype tag to the object.

·          GetStereotypes (): Returns the stereotype tag set of the object, of type StereotypeTag .

§   attributes [multiple]: Attributes of the object. The following functions allow us access to the component:

·          AddAttribute (String): Adds an attribute to the object.

·          GetAttributes (): Returns the set of attributes of the object of type AttributeItem .

§   operations [multiple]: Set of operations of the object. The interface functions of the component are:

·          AddOperation (String): Adds an operation to the object.

·          GetOperations (): Returns the set of operations of the type object OperationItem .

§   [multiple] interfaces : Interfaces of the object that can be visible from outside it. The available interface functions are:

·          AddInterface (String): Adds an interface to the object.

·          GetInterfaces (): Returns the set of interfaces of the type AttributeItem object .

§   realizations [multiple]: Set of classes that make the object. The following functions can be used to obtain and modify the component information:

·          AddRealization (String): Add a class to the object.

·          GetRealizations (): Returns the class set of the object of type AttributeItem .

§   artifacts [multiple]: Set of artifacts that manifest the object. The following functions are available for this component:

·          AddArtifact (String): Adds an artifact to the object.

·          GetArtifacts (): Returns the set of artifacts of the object of type AttributeItem .

§   [multiple] extension : Access to the extension point of an extended use case ( UMLUseCaseExtended ).

·          AddExtensionPoint (String): Adds an extension point to the use case.

·          GetExtensionPoints (): Returns the set of extension points of the extended use case.

§   guard [simple]: Saves the UML of the object. This component can be accessed through the following functions:

·          SetGuard (String): Set the text to save the UML of the object.

·          GetGuard (): Returns a string with the text corresponding to the object's guard.

§   tagValues ​​[multiple]: Set of tag values that an object has. The following functions are available for this component:

·          AddTagValue (String): Adds a value tag to the object.

·          GetTagValues ​​(): Returns the set of tag values of the object of type TagValueItem .

§   path [simple]: Path of an image associated with the object. This component can be accessed through the following functions:

·          SetPath (String): Set the path of the object.

·          GetPath (): Returns a string with the text corresponding to the path of the object.

 

       Although the above identifiers can be used for all types of final objects, be they of type Node , Relation or SuperNode , the following enumeration lists the identifiers that can only be used in case the final object is a relation (Relative):

 

§   roleA [simple]: Role of element A of the relation.

·          SetRolA (String): Sets the role of element A of the relation.

·          GetRolA (): Returns a string with the role of element A of the relation.

§   roleB [simple]: Role of element B of the relation.

·          SetRolB (String): Sets the role of element B of the relation.

·          GetRolB (): Returns a string with the role of element B of the relation.

§   multiplicityA [simple]: Multiplicity of element A of the relation.

·          SetMultiplicityA (String): Sets the multiplicity of element A of the relation.

·          GetMultiplicityA (): Returns a string with the multiplicity of element A of the relation.

§   multiplicityB [simple]: Multiplicity of element B of the relation.

·          SetMultiplicityB (String): Sets the multiplicity of element B of the relation.

·          GetMultiplicityB (): Returns a string with the multiplicity of element B of the relation.

 

      Note that in the specific case of components with multiple identifiers (marked by [multiple]), the get function returns a set of objects. Thus, to access the internal information contained in each of the objects, the getValue function of each of the objects returned by the get method can be invoked .

3.4.   Objects for the development of new elements

 

The objects explained here are the ones that the library has, along with its interface functions to define a new diagram or module from them. The basic objects such as Diagram, Node and Relation, as well as their derivatives, will be explained first, and then explain the components they define to add additional functionality.

Most of these objects have been explained in previous chapters of this manual,
so here we will only detail the functions necessary to design a new module.

 

3.4.1.   Diagram

 

It is a main object of the library, in charge of managing the elements of the diagram, as explained in section 3.1.1 . The specific functions of this object to define new diagrams are:

 

·          GetType (): String Returns the type assigned to the diagram. This type identifies the type of UML diagram in question. It can be modified using the setType () function .

·          GetValidElements (): Array Returns the type of UML elements that can be part of the diagram. It can be modified using the setValidElements () function .

·          SetName (String) It is the default name that the diagram will receive when it is created. It is advisable to use a representative name and not excessively long.

·          SetType (String) It is the function in charge of defining the type of the new diagram. The entered character string must exactly match the name that the constructor function receives.

·          SetValidElements (Array) Through this function the elements inserted in the diagram will be validated. It is important that the names of the elements match exactly those of your constructor function. Receives a vector string ( string ), where each is the name of an object.

 

3.4.2.   Do not give

 

It is every object in the shape of the library. There can be different types of nodes depending on their shape, but they all share the same interface.

 

·          AddComponent (Component) Adds a component to the node. Components are the way the library uses to add functionality to objects.

·            AddFigure (NodeFigure) Adds a graphical shape to the node. The figures were exposed in 3.15.

·            DelFigure (NodeFigure)  Deletes a graphic form of the node. Similarly, a figure can be added to the node using the addFigure () function . Figures are the way the library uses to graphically represent objects.

·            GetType (): String Returns the type assigned to the node. This type identifies the type of UML node in question. It can be modified using the setType () function .

·            IsAlone (): Boolean Returns true if the alone property has been enabled. False otherwise.

·            SetAlone ()   Enables the value of the alone property indicating that the node cannot be contained by another node. This property will be disabled by default, unless this method is invoked during node definition.

·          SetContainer () Converts the node to a container. Thus, since the node is created, it will be able to include any type of element that is created in the diagram.

·          SetHeight (Number) Defines the height of the node at the time of its creation.

·          SetMinWidth (Number) Defines the minimum width that the node should have. Note that this minimum width may vary if it contains components.

·          SetMinHeight (Number) Defines the minimum height that the node will have.

·          SetMoveable () Allows the user to modify the dimensions of the node.

·          SetProportional () Makes it mandatory for user size changes of the element to comply with the initial height / width ratio.

·          SetType (String) It is the function in charge of defining the type of element that is being created. The type indicated must exactly match the name that the constructor function receives.

·          SetWidth (Number) Defines the width of the node when it was created.

 

In addition, there are different types of nodes defined within the library, which provide different ways to interact with them by default.

 

Figure 3 . 3 : Main types of nodes

 

 

3.4.3.   Relationship

It is any relationship between two nodes or between a node and a relationship. The library implements the following common interface:

 

·          AddStereotype (String) Adds a stereotype to the relation. It can be modified and add more stereotypes by the user.

·          

·          GetType (): String Returns the type assigned to the UML relation. It can be modified using the setType () function .

·          SetComponentName (String) Creates the name component, if it does not exist, and defines the name of the relationship. You can go without parameters, in which case the empty component will also be created.

·          SetEnd (RelationEnd) Defines the style of the end of the relation using an object of type RelationEnd .

·          SetLine (RelationLine) Defines the line style (continuous, dashed, etc.) of the relation using an object of type RelationLine , the available types will be explained later.

·          SetMultiplicityA (String) Defines the multiplicity of the first element of the relation. It can go without parameters, in which case the empty component to be filled by the user will be created.

·          SetMultiplicityB (String) Defines the multiplicity of the second element of the relation.

·          SetRoleA (String) Defines the role of the first element of the relation. It can go without parameters, in which case the empty component to be filled by the user will be created.

·          SetRoleB (String) Defines the role of the second element of the relation.

·          SetStart (RelationEnd) Defines the style of the beginning of the relation ( pitch tip, closed tip, etc.), using an object of type RelationEnd .

·          SetStereotype (String) Defines the stereotype of the relation. It cannot be modified by the user.

·          SetType (String) It is the function in charge of defining the type of element that is being created. The type you enter must exactly match the name your constructor function receives.

 

 

3.4.4.   Component

 

This object is an essential piece when defining new objects in the library. Its purpose is to add functionality to the element where it is defined, usually in the form of static or editable text. It can have different shapes and positions within the element. The parameters that can be passed to the constructor, using JSON notation, are:

 

·          Id (String) Defines the identifier of the component. It is mandatory to define it for components that can be edited by the user. Note that an identifier cannot be repeated within the same element.

·          Margin (Number) Defines the margin applied to said component, referred to the number of pixels of separation between the component and all the elements that surround it.

·          Position (Component.position) Defines the position of the component within the element, being TopRigth, Bottom, Static or, by default, Float.

·          Centered (Boolean) In case it is positioned as Component.Float, this parameter defines if the component will be centered horizontally within the element.

·          Text (String) The text string that the component will contain. Only valid for components with text.

 

There are different types of components within the library, many of which are for very specific use. The most common are:


Text
 This component represents only a text box not editable by the user.


TextBox
 This component represents a user-editable text box. Its content can be any text string that is entered on a single line. The string is not formatted.


TextArea
 This component represents a user editable text area. Its content can be any text string that is entered in the number of lines you want, without being restricted.

 

TextFields
 This component represents a variable set of text strings. Its content can be edited by the user, in addition to adding and removing text boxes. Its content is not restricted.


StereotypeFields
 It is a variable set of stereotypes, editable by the user. Its content conforms to the stereotypes defined by UML 2.


ComponentSymbol
 Adds a representative icon of a component type element in the UML 2 standard.


AttributeFields
 Allows a variable set of text strings restricted to the format that an attribute must fulfill, according to the UML 2 standard. The different attributes can be hidden by means of a button specially indicated for this purpose. Editing by the user of this component is guided by a form.

Special parameters:

·          Visible (Boolean) Defines the default visibility of the attributes.


OperationFields
 It is a component that allows a variable set of text strings according to the format of operations prescribed by the UML 2 standard. Different operations can be hidden using a button. Editing by the user of this component is guided by a form.

11.3.              Estereotipos

 

       Además de las propiedades comunes a todos los objetos finales, nótese que también se dispone de propiedades de estereotipado mediante el uso de perfiles UML. A continuación se presentan las funciones de interfaz que hacen posible el estereotipado de los distintos objetos finales de la librería, pero antes se debe puntualizar la nomenclatura utilizada en el ámbito de los estereotipos dentro de jsUML2.

 

§  Objeto estereotipo: representa al objeto final de la librería UMLStereotype presente en un perfil UML. Puede ser aplicado sobre un elemento estereotipable mediante las funciones applyStereotype() y notado en forma de imagen icónica mediante showStereotype. Los objetos estereotipo pueden contener propiedades en forma de valores etiquetados (tag values) que serán impuestos sobre aquellos elementos que los apliquen.

§  Etiqueta estereotipo: representa a un componente de tipo StereotypeItem y que puede ser añadido en cualquier objeto final, exista o no perfil UML que lo defina. Este componente es únicamente una etiqueta que contiene un texto nunca representable como imagen, y puede ser creado de varias formas:

 

·         El programador crea manualmente una etiqueta estereotipo mediante la función de interfaz addStereotype (sección 3.2.

·         La etiqueta estereotipo es creada dentro de un elemento final con la aplicación de un estereotipo como parte de la definición del elemento UML2. Dicha etiqueta estereotipo contendrá el nombre del objeto estereotipo como texto. 

 

       Una vez se ha hecho esta distinción, las funciones de interfaz son detalladas para el caso de los objetos estereotipo definidos en un perfil UML existente.

 

§  getStereotypeProperties( Element ) : Array Devuelve la lista de estereotipos que pueden ser aplicados al elemento pasado como parámetro.

§  setStereotypeProperties( Node, array): Establece todas las propiedades de estereotipado para un objeto final de tipo nodo (primer parámetro), así como el conjunto de objetos estereotipo que van a ser aplicados a dicho objeto (segundo parámetro). Cada uno de los objetos estereotipo incluidos en el objeto array es de tipo UMLStereotype (sección 10.3). Así este parámetro permite que el objeto pasado en el primer parámetro haga uso de las funciones de interfaz presentadas a continuación.

§  setStereotypesProfile( array ): Establece los objetos estereotipo que pueden ser aplicados a un objeto final.  El parámetro pasado a la función contiene dichos objetos estereotipo en un array.

§  applyStereotype( Stereotype ): Aplica el objeto estereotipo pasado como parámetro al objeto final, añadiendo tanto los tag values de dicho objeto estereotipo como nombre del estereotipo al objeto final.  

§  isDrawableStereotype(): Indica si el objeto final que ha llamado a esta función es un elemento que puede cambiar su representación gráfica haciendo uso de una imagen asociada a un objeto estereotipo.

§  showStereotype( Stereotype ): Representa gráficamente el objeto final haciendo uso de la imagen asociada al objeto estereotipo pasado como parámetro. Como requisito imprescindible a cumplir, el estereotipo debe haber sido aplicado a dicho objeto final anteriormente.

§  removeStereotype( Stereotype ):  Borra toda la información que contiene un objeto final sobre el objeto estereotipo pasado como parámetro. Entre la información a borrar se encuentran los tag values, la imagen y la etiqueta estereotipo asociados al objeto estereotipo. Para borrar esta información satisfactoriamente se tiene que cumplir que el objeto estereotipo haya sido previamente aplicado al objeto final.

§  showTagValuesDialog(): Muestra un cuadro de diálogo al usuario que contiene los distintos tag values del objeto final. Además, muestra el valor asociado a cada tag value y permite la modificación de dicho valor. Es una función orientada a la interfaz de usuario.

§  showApplyStereotypesDialog(): Muestra un cuadro de diálogo con los distintos objetos estereotipo que pueden ser aplicados a un objeto final y realiza las acciones necesarias para aplicar un objeto estereotipo elegido por el usuario a un objeto final. Es una función orientada a la interfaz de usuario.

§  showStereotypesDialog(): Muestra un cuadro de diálogo con todos los objetos estereotipo que han sido aplicados previamente a un objeto final, y realiza las acciones necesarias para que dicho objeto final sea representado gráficamente con la imagen que contiene un objeto estereotipo elegido por el usuario. Es una función orientada a la interfaz de usuario.

12.   CASO DE ESTUDIO: Editor UML simple

 

 

       En este capítulo se expondrá un ejemplo práctico de la librería, para lo que se hará uso de la aplicación de ejemplo creada en el desarrollo previo de ésta [11] y consistente en un editor ligero básico de UML2. Así, se detallarán las funciones principales que ofrece la librería, tanto si se trata de nuevas funcionalidades como de funcionalidades incorporadas con anterioridad a las que se haya hecho alguna mejora, especificando el código necesario para cada una de ellas. Sin embargo, no se expondrá todo el código de la aplicación, sino que únicamente nos centraremos en el código correspondiente a cada una de las funcionalidades explicadas, para obtener una visión más general y clara. Si en algún momento es necesario mirar la totalidad del código de la aplicación, recuerde que éste se encuentra disponible en el directorio /src/app.

       En este punto, es importante observar el carácter modular que presenta la librería y, por ello, se debe diseñar una aplicación que se comunique con la capa superior de jsUML2, tal y como se muestra en la Figura 12.1. De esta forma, la interacción entre la aplicación y la librería se lleva a cabo a través de la capa UDModules, capa superior de la librería que contiene las clases finales de UML2, pero nunca accediendo directamente al núcleo.
